td.paragraph: This assay is performed using extracted DNA followed by "real time" PCR testing. The target sequences are the glycoprotein D and glycoprotein G genes of herpes simplex virus, with differentiation between HSV I and HSV II possible. The performance characteristics of this assay were determined by Children's Medical Center Dallas, Advanced Diagnostics laboratory. The HSV PCR test should not be positive in the CSF of healthy individuals. The limit of detection is approximately 100 viral targets of HSV I per mL of sample and 1000 targets of HSV II per mL of sample. A negative result does not rule out the presence of PCR inhibitors in the patient specimen or herpes nucleic acid in concentrations below the level of detection of the assay.

The results are not intended to be used as the sole means for clinical diagnosis or patient management decision. Analyte Specific Reagents (ASR) are used in many lab tests necessary for standard medical care and generally do not require U.S. Food and Drug Administration approval. Children's Medical Center Dallas is authorized under the Clinical Laboratory Improvement Amendments (CLIA) to perform high-complexity testing. This test should not be regarded as investigational or for research use. It is performed pursuant to an agreement with Roche Molecular Systems, Inc.
